<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,2045]" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,455,224,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Roza &amp; Mermudes, 2019" authorityName="Roza &amp; Mermudes" authorityYear="2019" box="[471,700,224,250]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mesochila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="297" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moraveci" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[471,700,224,250]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">Mesochila moraveci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[708,799,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[708,799,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="297" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="W. Horn" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[950,1176,224,251]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mesochila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="295" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipennis" subGenus="Mesochila">
<emphasis box="[950,973,225,250]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">M</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[998,1021,225,250]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">M</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1046,1176,224,250]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">brevipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paraguay-Amambay, Canindeyu and Concepcion" baseAuthorityName="Sawada &amp; Wiesner" baseAuthorityYear="1997" box="[1190,1388,224,251]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mesochila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="295" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="drechseli" subGenus="Mesochila">
<emphasis box="[1190,1213,225,250]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">M</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1238,1261,225,250]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">M</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1286,1388,224,250]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">drechseli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brazil-Mato Grosso" baseAuthorityName="W. Horn" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[151,358,260,287]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mesochila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="295" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prepusula" subGenus="Mesochila">
<emphasis box="[151,174,261,286]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">M</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[199,222,261,286]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">M</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[247,358,260,286]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">prepusula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its comparatively short and narrow aedeagus, with a thick, moderately hooked apex (Figs 6 and 7), and the internal sac with three distinct sclerites characteristic of the species-complex: a ventral spur with double-wing “stingray-like” base, an oval upper sclerite with a echinulate surface and a dorso-basal semitriangular piece (Fig. 7). Externally, it is most easily distinguished from these three species by the distinct humeral band (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1943,1968]" captionTargetBox="[185,1397,175,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[175,1411,166,1924]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Mesochila (Mesochila) moraveci sp. nov., Holotype male from Brazil, Caracol-PI. 1, habitus, dorsal view; 2, head, frontodorsal view; 3, clypeous and labrum, frontal view; 4, pronotum, dorsal view; 5, elytron, dorsal view; 6, aedeagus dry, left lateral view; 7, aedeagus sclerites, left lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3516066" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3516066/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">Fig. 1 and 5</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Moravec" authorityYear="2018" box="[261,378,404,430]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mesochila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="297" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[261,378,404,430]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">Mesochila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[395,418,405,430]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">M</emphasis>
,) 
<emphasis box="[443,572,404,430]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">brasiliensis</emphasis>
(Dejean, 1825) and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schilder, 1953)" authorityName="Schilder" authorityYear="1953" baseAuthorityName="Schilder" baseAuthorityYear="1953" box="[807,1380,404,431]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mesochila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="297" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horni" subGenus="Paramesochila">
<emphasis box="[807,924,404,430]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">Mesochila</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[941,1111,404,430]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">Paramesochila</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1128,1189,404,430]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">horni</emphasis>
(Schilder, 1953)
</taxonomicName>
possesses similar humeral band, but can be distinguished by their very different aedeagi; moreover, the former also by its different pronotal surface, the latter by its more elongate pronotum and more uneven elytral surface. In addition, none of these externally similar species have the whitish lateromedian macula prolonged along the outer margin in form of a thin stripe as it is in the new species (
<figureCitation box="[681,743,548,575]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1943,1968]" captionTargetBox="[185,1397,175,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[175,1411,166,1924]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Mesochila (Mesochila) moraveci sp. nov., Holotype male from Brazil, Caracol-PI. 1, habitus, dorsal view; 2, head, frontodorsal view; 3, clypeous and labrum, frontal view; 4, pronotum, dorsal view; 5, elytron, dorsal view; 6, aedeagus dry, left lateral view; 7, aedeagus sclerites, left lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3516066" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3516066/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="297">Fig.5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
